<section class="hero">
  <h1>The Bitcoin Retirement <em>Stress Test</em></h1>
  <div class="hero-subtitle">The retirement calculator shows the upside path. This one drops a bear market into it, at the worst possible moment.</div>
  <p class="subtitle">Two retirees with the identical average return can end up in completely different places. The one who hit a deep crash in the <em>first</em> years of retirement was selling into the low to fund income, permanently shrinking the base that later had to recover. The one who hit the same crash <em>late</em> was barely touched. When you are withdrawing, the order of returns matters.</p>
</section>

<main class="content-area">

  {% include 'components/tool-framing.njk' %}

  <!-- ════════ 1. INTRO ════════ -->
  <div class="section-intro st-prose">
    <p>This is <strong>sequence-of-returns risk</strong>, and it is specifically a withdrawal problem. While you are still buying, a crash is a discount. Once you are selling Bitcoin to live, a crash means selling <em>more</em> sats to cover the same bill, and that is stack you never get back even if price fully recovers. For Bitcoin the effect is sharper than for most assets, because its drawdowns are deep (the 77% historical characteristic from <a href="/bull-and-bear-cycles">Bull &amp; Bear Cycles</a>) and its recoveries, while historically reliable, are not guaranteed.</p>
    <p>So pick a crash, drop it anywhere in the retirement, and watch what it does. This is a what-if, not a forecast. It assigns no odds, and it is built to show the cases where the plan fails as plainly as the cases where it survives.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- ════════ 2. YOUR PLAN ════════ -->
  <section class="st-section" id="plan">
    <div class="st-eyebrow">Your plan</div>
    <h2 class="st-h2">Start from a retirement plan</h2>
    <p class="st-lead">The baseline, before any crash. These are the same inputs as the Retirement calculator, so the no-crash path here matches that page.</p>
    <div class="st-inputs">
      <label class="st-field"><span>Bitcoin stack (BTC)</span><input type="number" id="stStack" step="0.01" min="0.01"></label>
      <label class="st-field"><span>Retirement year</span><input type="number" id="stRetire" step="1" min="2026" max="2100"></label>
      <label class="st-field"><span>Years in retirement</span><input type="number" id="stYears" step="1" min="1" max="60"></label>
      <label class="st-field"><span>Target annual income (USD)</span><input type="number" id="stIncome" step="1000" min="0"></label>
      <label class="st-field"><span>Monthly DCA until retirement (USD)</span><input type="number" id="stDca" step="100" min="0"></label>
      <div class="st-field">
        <span>Income target is in</span>
        <div class="st-seg" id="stIncomeBasis">
          <button type="button" data-val="today">Today&rsquo;s dollars</button>
          <button type="button" data-val="fixed">Fixed future $</button>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ 3. THE STRESS TEST ════════ -->
  <section class="st-section" id="stress">
    <div class="st-eyebrow">The stress test</div>
    <h2 class="st-h2">Now drop a bear market into it</h2>
    <p class="st-lead">You pick the crash. The tool never predicts one. Depth and recovery come from the historical record; timing is the variable nobody can know in advance, which is exactly the point.</p>

    <div class="st-controls">
      <div class="st-control">
        <div class="st-control-label">Crash depth</div>
        <div class="st-seg" id="stDepth">
          <button type="button" data-val="40">&minus;40%</button>
          <button type="button" data-val="60">&minus;60%</button>
          <button type="button" data-val="77">&minus;77%</button>
          <button type="button" data-val="custom">Custom</button>
        </div>
        <div class="st-custom" id="stDepthCustomWrap" hidden><input type="number" id="stDepthCustom" min="1" max="99" step="1" placeholder="55"> <span>% peak-to-trough</span></div>
        <p class="st-control-note">&minus;77% is Bitcoin&rsquo;s historical bear-market characteristic, not a forecast. See the evidence on <a href="/bull-and-bear-cycles">Bull &amp; Bear Cycles</a>.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="st-control st-control-key">
        <div class="st-control-label">Crash timing <span class="st-key-tag">the decisive variable</span></div>
        <div class="st-seg" id="stTiming">
          <button type="button" data-val="1">Year 1</button>
          <button type="button" data-val="3">Year 3</button>
          <button type="button" data-val="5">Year 5</button>
          <button type="button" data-val="10">Year 10</button>
          <button type="button" data-val="custom">Custom</button>
        </div>
        <div class="st-custom" id="stTimingCustomWrap" hidden><input type="number" id="stTimingCustom" min="1" max="60" step="1" placeholder="7"> <span>year of retirement</span></div>
        <p class="st-control-note">Which year of retirement the bear market begins. Early is brutal, late is nearly harmless. The timing sensitivity below is the core lesson.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="st-control">
        <div class="st-control-label">Recovery</div>
        <div class="st-seg" id="stRecovery">
          <button type="button" data-val="fast">Fast</button>
          <button type="button" data-val="historical">Historical</button>
          <button type="button" data-val="slow">Slow</button>
          <button type="button" data-val="weak">Weak</button>
        </div>
        <p class="st-control-note"><strong>Weak</strong> never fully returns to trend, the failed-recovery case. Historical is the default because past recoveries were reliable, but non-stationarity means the future is not guaranteed.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="st-assumptions" id="stAssumptions">&mdash;</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ 4. THE TWO PATHS ════════ -->
  <section class="st-section" id="paths">
    <div class="st-eyebrow">The two paths</div>
    <h2 class="st-h2">What the crash costs</h2>
    <div class="st-headline st-out-ok" id="stHeadline">&mdash;</div>
    <div class="st-chart-wrap" data-chart-copy data-chart-title="Retirement stress test: baseline vs. crashed path" data-chart-filename="retirement-stress-test.png"><canvas id="stChart"></canvas></div>
    <p class="st-chart-caption">Stack value over retirement, log scale, nominal dollars. The <strong style="color:#6db3d4">baseline</strong> is the plan with no crash; the <strong style="color:#e08a7a">crashed path</strong> is the same plan with your bear market. The gap between them is the sequence-of-returns cost. Faint lines are the Power Law trend and floor.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ 5. TIMING SENSITIVITY ════════ -->
  <section class="st-section" id="timing">
    <div class="st-eyebrow">Timing sensitivity</div>
    <h2 class="st-h2">The same crash, at different years</h2>
    <p class="st-lead">This is the whole point. Hold the depth and recovery fixed, move only <em>when</em> the crash lands, and the outcomes diverge wildly. A crash early in retirement can break a plan that the identical crash, late, barely dents. Timing is decisive, and it is unknowable in advance.</p>
    <div class="st-timing-grid">
      <div class="st-chart-wrap st-timing-chart" data-chart-copy data-chart-title="Sequence risk: same crash at different retirement years" data-chart-filename="sequence-risk-timing.png"><canvas id="stTimingChart"></canvas></div>
      <div class="st-timing-tablewrap">
        <table class="st-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Crash in</th><th>Calendar</th><th>Outcome</th><th class="st-num">Final stack</th><th class="st-num">Income lost</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody id="stTimingTableBody"></tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="st-chart-caption">Final stack in today&rsquo;s dollars for the same crash landing in different years of retirement. Bars below the dashed <strong>no-crash baseline</strong> are the cost of that timing; <span class="st-fail">red</span> bars ran the stack to zero. &ldquo;Income lost&rdquo; is the shortfall versus baseline, in years of your target income.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ 6. AUDIT VIEW ════════ -->
  <section class="st-section" id="audit">
    <button class="st-audit-toggle" id="stAuditToggle" aria-expanded="false">
      <span class="st-audit-label">Verify the math</span>
      <span class="st-audit-hint">year-by-year, crashed path. The crash years show the depressed price and the extra BTC sold.</span>
    </button>
    <div id="stAuditBody2" hidden>
      <div class="st-audit-actions">
        <button type="button" class="st-csv-btn" id="stCsvBtn"><span class="st-csv-label">Download CSV</span></button>
      </div>
      <div class="st-table-scroll">
        <table class="st-table st-audit-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Year</th><th class="st-num">BTC price</th><th class="st-num">Income drawn</th><th class="st-num">BTC sold</th><th class="st-num">BTC left</th><th class="st-num">Stack USD</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody id="stAuditBody"></tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="st-chart-caption"><span class="st-dot">▼</span> marks years the crash has depressed the price below trend. Notice the <strong>BTC sold</strong> column rise in those years: the same income now costs more sats. That is the mechanism, sequence risk made concrete.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ 7. WHAT THIS MEANS ════════ -->
  <section class="st-section" id="means">
    <div class="st-eyebrow">What this means</div>
    <h2 class="st-h2">Reading the result</h2>
    <div class="st-prose st-prose-wide">
      <p>A plan that survives a mid-severity crash in year 10 tells you little about the same plan meeting a deep crash in year 1. The tool exists to show that spread, including the outcomes where the stack does not make it. If your plan only survives on the assumption of a fast recovery, that is worth knowing now, while you can still change the stack, the income, or the horizon.</p>
      <p>Two honest framings sit side by side here. A badly-timed crash can do real, lasting damage to a Bitcoin retirement. And the same crash, met late or with room to spare, is nearly a non-event. Both are true; which one you get is a matter of timing you cannot control.</p>
      <p class="st-v2">There is a lever this version does not yet model: <strong>reducing withdrawals during the crash</strong> rather than selling a fixed amount into the low. A future version will add it, the actionable counterpart to the &ldquo;don&rsquo;t sell into the bottom&rdquo; lesson from Bull &amp; Bear. For now, treat the fixed-withdrawal result as the cautious case.</p>
    </div>
